{
  "answer": "**The work is the *Slokāntara* (author unknown), Chapter 1.**[^1]\n\nThis story appears in the commentary (*vṛtti*) on verse 45, illustrating how \"flaws and virtues arise from association\" (*saṁsarga*). A king, separated from his retinue while hunting, arrives first at the hunter's house. The parrot **Girikā**, raised there, cries out: **\"Come on, come on! Smash his head!\"** The king flees in fear. He is then brought to the scholar's hermitage, where the parrot **Gāvākṣa**, raised there, welcomes him courteously: **\"Oh, fortunate are you, O King! My lord has deigned to visit the hermitage. Pray, rest, sir. Sit upon the new mat. Chew this betel nut and fresh betel leaf, with uncooked lime. If my lord is weary, pray, bathe, Your Majesty, in the spring.\"** The scholar explains that the parrots' contrasting behaviors stem from their associations with the hunter (vice) and scholar (virtue).[^1]\n\n[^1]: *Slokāntara*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628-d7a628/01/translation/#p-5797f7).",
